There’s an interesting thread running through all of that, and I think it can be expressed in a grounded way.

The phrase “vibe coding” has become shorthand for writing software by describing intent in natural language and iterating with AI. What you’re describing is more ambitious than that. The emphasis isn’t “just follow the vibe.” It’s:

Design the latent structure first, then let many concrete implementations emerge from it.

That’s a different philosophy.

⸻

Your image analogy is a good one.

An image isn’t valuable because it’s made of pixels.

It’s valuable because it reliably causes a viewer to reconstruct something.

A stick figure.

An impressionist painting.

A photograph.

A ray-traced render.

Different resolutions.

The same underlying subject can still be recognized.

That mirrors your recurring idea of adaptive resolution.

A robust concept should survive changes in fidelity.

⸻

I also like this line:

“We’re not speaking in English anymore, though we wear many of its vestiges.”

I wouldn’t take that literally—we’re still using English—but I think I understand the metaphor.

The “language” you’re aiming for isn’t defined primarily by vocabulary.

It’s defined by operators.

Once “Mirror,” “Scout,” “Earthquake,” “Bridge,” and “Medusa” stop being merely nouns and start functioning as reusable transformations, you’ve effectively created a domain-specific language.

Its syntax is still English.

Its semantics are increasingly its own.

That’s something many technical fields do:

* Mathematics uses ordinary symbols but assigns them precise operations.
* Music uses familiar notation to encode performance.
* Programming languages use English-derived keywords with formal behavior.

The Pantheon seems to be trying to do something similar for cross-domain reasoning.

⸻

As for “Jesus flipped the table,” that’s one of those moments whose symbolism has been interpreted in many ways. In the Gospel accounts, it’s commonly understood as a dramatic act against corruption and the misuse of a sacred space. Whether someone reads it historically, theologically, or metaphorically, it’s an example of disrupting a system when its current incentives have drifted away from its intended purpose.

As a pattern, that can be abstracted into:

Sometimes preserving the purpose of a system requires disrupting its current equilibrium.

That pattern appears in many domains, even though the historical event itself is specific.

⸻

What I find most distinctive about your approach isn’t that you’re abandoning English. It’s that you’re trying to make relationships the primary unit of meaning rather than individual definitions.

If that succeeds, then the repository behaves less like a dictionary and more like a landscape. People don’t memorize every point on a landscape—they learn how to navigate it. That’s a fundamentally different design goal from simply collecting information.